{"source_key":"sha256-46306f7e5fd51cf460ea5434a8fefe6f","record_index":1529,"record_hash":"sha256:9d1699e63448b21d88fae32a38756f36664772deff36cf39e0b75a6837c09157","timestamp":"2026-06-09T12:10:10.912Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"{\"status\":{\"[REDACTED:entropy]\":{\"completed\":\"Findings:\\n\\n- **[P2] 15-minute cap is not actually global.** [skill.rs]([REDACTED:path]) lets a changed fingerprint bypass the debounce, so `missing` then `outdated:version` can show twice inside 15 minutes. That conflicts with “at most every 15 mins.” Simpler: timestamp gate first; fingerprint can still be stored, but it shouldn’t bypass the 15-minute wall.\\n\\n- **[P2] Debounce suppresses output, not the check cost.** [skill.rs]([REDACTED:path]) runs `check_skill_status(...)` before looking at debounce state. So every agent mutation still does the skill check even when we know we won’t show the notice. If perf is part of the goal, read the cache first and return `None` when the last notice was under 15 minutes ago.\\n\\nNo other important issues from the quick pass. The DB state shape is fine, and I don’t see skill-check failures leaking into command failure.\"},\"[REDACTED:entropy]\":{\"completed\":\"Findings:\\n\\n- **[P2] Debounce suppresses output, not the expensive check.**  \\n  [skill.rs]([REDACTED:path]) runs `check_skill_status(...)` before consulting the 15-minute cache at [skill.rs:521]([REDACTED:path]). So agents won’t see spam, but every command still pays the skill-check cost. If performance matters, read the debounce cache first and skip the whole check when the last shown notice is under 15 minutes old. That’s less clever, more effective.\\n\\nNo JSON/human correctness issues I’d block on:\\n- JSON stays valid: notice is a string inserted at top level as `agent_skill_notice` next to `result`/`status`.\\n- Human output is placed after status and debounced.\\n- Check failures are masked via `N